Article 6.07. Passing on opposite courses in a narrow passage

1 In this Article, a narrow section is understood to mean a section of or a place in the waterway where the waterway does not provide sufficient space for two vessels or two convoys to pass each other. A section of or a place in the waterway indicated by the sign A.4 or A.4.1 ( Appendix 7 ) and the passage opening of a bridge in the open position and a lock or weir that is open on both sides and for which two green fixed lights are displayed above each other in accordance with the sign E.1 ( Appendix 7 ) are a narrow section.

2 The fifth, sixth, seventh and eighth paragraphs of this Article shall not apply to narrow passages where passage is regulated by means of signs.

3 A vessel must pass through a strait without undue delay, provided that passing is prohibited.

4 If the view is not clear, a vessel shall, before entering a strait, give one long blast. If necessary, especially when the strait is long, she shall repeat this signal while passing through.

5 When passing through a narrow passage on a waterway with a current, a vessel sailing against the current must give way to a vessel sailing in front of the current.

6 When passing through a narrow passage on a waterway without current, a small vessel must give way to a large vessel approaching on the opposite course.

7 When sailing through a narrow passage on a waterway where there is no current:

a.a large motor vessel encountering an obstacle on the starboard side or having the inside of a bend on the starboard side shall give way to a large vessel approaching on the opposite course;

b.to give way to a large motor vessel approaching on the opposite course and having entered the strait;

c.to give way to a large sailing vessel which has not sailed the strait to a large vessel approaching on the opposite course;

d.to give way to a large sailing vessel sailing on the starboard tack and having sailed the strait, approaching on the opposite course, sailing on the port tack and having also sailed the strait.

8 When sailing through a narrow passage on a waterway where there is no current:

a.a small motor vessel encountering an obstacle on the starboard side or having the inside bend on the starboard side of a bend shall give way to another small motor vessel approaching on the opposite course;

b.a small muscle-powered vessel encountering an obstacle on the starboard side or having the inside of a bend on the starboard side shall give way to another small muscle-powered vessel approaching on the opposite course;

c.a small motor vessel or a small vessel propelled by muscle power to give way to a small sailing vessel approaching on the opposite course and having sailed through the strait;

d.to give way to a small motor vessel over a small muscle-powered vessel approaching on the opposite course;

e.to give way to a small sailing vessel which has not sailed the strait to a small vessel approaching on the opposite course;

f.to give way to a small sailing vessel sailing on the starboard tack and having sailed the strait, approaching on the opposite course, sailing on the port tack and having also sailed the strait.

Article 6.09. Overtaking; general provisions (translated from Dutch)

A vessel may only overtake another vessel after having satisfied itself that this can be done without danger.

overtake: the approach by one vessel of another vessel from a direction more than 22°30´ astern of that vessel's beam;

Action by Stand-on vessel

A large vessel overtaken by a large vessel and any small vessel overtaken shall, as far as is necessary and possible, facilitate the passing. She shall reduce speed if this is necessary to effect the passing without danger and in so short a time as not to hinder other vessels

overtake: the approach by one vessel of another vessel from a direction more than 22°30´ astern of that vessel's beam;

Rule 6
Safe Speed
Every vessel shall at all times proceed at a safe speed so that she can take proper and effective action
to avoid collision and be stopped within a distance appropriate to the prevailing circumstances and
conditions. In determining a safe speed the following factors shall be among those taken into
account:
(a) By all vessels:
(i) the state of visibility;
(ii) the traffic density including concentrations of fishing vessels or any other vessels;
(iii) the manoeuvrability of the vessel with special reference to stopping distance and turning
ability in the prevailing conditions;
(iv) at night the presence of background light such as from shore lights or from back scatter
of her own lights;
(v) the state of wind, sea and current, and the proximity of navigational hazards;
(vi) the draught in relation to the available depth of water.
(b) Additionally, by vessels with operational radar:(i) the characteristics, efficiency and limitations of the radar equipment;
(ii) any constraints imposed by the radar range scale in use;
(iii) the effect on radar detection of the sea state, weather and other sources of interference;
(iv) the possibility that small vessels, ice and other floating objects may not be detected by
radar at an adequate range;
(v) the number, location and movement of vessels detected by radar;
(vi) the more exact assessment of the visibility that may be possible when radar is used to
determine the range of vessels or other objects in the vicinity.
